The '''Green-legged Partridge''' is an old Polish [[list of chicken breeds|breed]] of [[chicken]]. It is characterised by the unusual [[reseda green]] colour of the [[wikt:shank|shank]]s.{{r|siwek|page=522|fao}}

== History ==

The Green-legged Partridge was first described by {{ill|Bronisław Obfidowicz|pl}} in 1879.{{r|dad|dad2}} In 1894 a flock was shown by Roman Ujejski at the {{ill|General Provincial Exhibition, Lviv|pl|Powszechna Wystawa Krajowa we Lwowie|lt=General Provincial Exhibition}} in [[Lviv]]. A [[breed standard]] was drawn up by [[Maurycy Trybulski]] in 1921,{{r|fao}} and the breed was officially recognised in 1923.{{r|dad}} From 1930 it was raised in some 70% of the country. However, egg production was found to be variable, and the birds did not adapt well to [[intensive farming|intensive management]]. Numbers declined; between 1961 and 1973 its percentage of the national chicken population fell from 11.4% to 1–2%.{{r|fao}} Conservation efforts began in the 1970s.{{r|fao}}

Between 1946 and 1954 Laura Kaufman [[cross-breeding|crossed]] the Green-legged Partridge breed with American [[Plymouth Rock (chicken)|Plymouth Rock]] birds to create the [[Polbar]]. The aim was to introduce the barred gene of the Plymouth Rock to make chicks [[auto-sexing]] – female Polbar chicks can be distinguished from males at one day old by the longer black eye-stripe.{{r|dad|mag}}

There are two strains of the Green-legged Partridge, each with one flock; both populations are closed.{{r|fao}} The ZK strain has since 1945 been kept at Felin near [[Lublin]], in the eastern part of the country, by the [[University of Life Sciences in Lublin|University of Life Sciences]] of that city. It is kept for conservation only. At the end of 2014 there were {{val|1170}} birds.{{r|dad}} The Z11 strain was kept at [[Życzyn]] from 1972 until 1995, when it was moved to the {{ill|National Research Institute of Animal Production|pl|Instytut Zootechniki – Państwowy Instytut Badawczy}} experimental station in [[Chorzelów]].{{r|fao}}

== Use ==

The Green-legged Partridge is well adapted to [[extensive farming|extensive]] management; it [[forage]]s well and is resistant to disease.{{r|dad}} It is not suited to intensive management, and becomes subject to [[Cannibalism in poultry|cannibalism]], feather loss and feather-pulling if kept closely enclosed.{{r|fao}} Egg-laying performance is generally poor;{{r|fao}} the [[yolk]] of the eggs has a low [[cholesterol]] content compared to that found in other breeds.{{r|dad}} Both meat and eggs have good flavour. The breed is kept only for reasons of [[Conservation biology|conservation]].{{r|dad}}

